We need to construct a new homotopy operator such that h'  \circ  h' = 0 and h'  \circ  (d_C +  \delta _C)  \circ  h' = h'. We approach this through a “perturbative” mindset. Starting with h_0 = h, the second equation is off by a difference of h_0  \delta _C h_0. We simply add this as a correction term, h_1 = h_0 +  \alpha  h_0  \delta _C h_0 where \alpha is some coefficient. (Note that essentially the only terms we can consider are of the form h_0  \delta _C h_0  \delta _C  \cdots  h_0, since nothing else has the same type.) We still have h_1  \circ  h_1 = 0, and for the second equation this creates a new error term
\begin {aligned}       & \quad  h_1 (d_C +  \delta _C) h_1 - h_1  \\        &= (1 +  \alpha ) h_0  \delta _C h_0 + 2 ( \alpha  +  \alpha ^2) h_0  \delta _C h_0  \delta _C h_0 +  \alpha ^2 h_0  \delta _C h_0  \delta _C h_0  \delta _C h_0      \end {aligned}
and we can eliminate the first and second order part by setting \alpha  = -1. The natural next step would be to add a further correction h_2 = h_1 +  \beta  h_0  \delta _C h_0  \delta _C h_0. This turns out to require \beta  = +1, and so on.

We need to construct a new homotopy operator such that h'  \circ  h' = 0 and h'  \circ  (d_C +  \delta _C)  \circ  h' = h'. We approach this through a “perturbative” mindset. Starting with h_0 = h, the second equation is off by a difference of h_0  \delta _C h_0. We simply add this as a correction term, h_1 = h_0 +  \alpha  h_0  \delta _C h_0 where \alpha is some coefficient. (Note that essentially the only terms we can consider are of the form h_0  \delta _C h_0  \delta _C  \cdots  h_0, since nothing else has the same type.) We still have h_1  \circ  h_1 = 0, and for the second equation this creates a new error term
\begin {aligned}       & \quad  h_1 (d_C +  \delta _C) h_1 - h_1  \\        &= (1 +  \alpha ) h_0  \delta _C h_0 + 2 ( \alpha  +  \alpha ^2) h_0  \delta _C h_0  \delta _C h_0 +  \alpha ^2 h_0  \delta _C h_0  \delta _C h_0  \delta _C h_0      \end {aligned}
and we can eliminate the first and second order part by setting \alpha  = -1. The natural next step would be to add a further correction h_2 = h_1 +  \beta  h_0  \delta _C h_0  \delta _C h_0. This turns out to require \beta  = +1, and so on.

A chain reduction consists of maps C_k  \mathrel { \smash { \xtofrom [g_k]{f_k}}} D_k such that f_k  \circ  g_k =  \operatorname {id}. Therefore C_ \bullet splits as D_ \bullet   \oplus  E_ \bullet, and the boundary maps are preserved since f, g are chain maps. We have a homotopy h_k : D_k  \oplus  E_k  \to  D_{k+1}  \oplus  E_{k+1}, which we may write as a (2  \times  2)-matrix. f  \circ  h = 0 demands the first row to be zero, and h  \circ  g = 0 requires the first column to vanish. This leaves us with
\begin {bmatrix}       0 & 0  \\        0 & r_k      \end {bmatrix}
such that r_{k+1}  \circ  r_k = 0, since h  \circ  h = 0.

On the other hand, given only the homotopy operator, we expect to have d  \circ  h + h  \circ  d =  \operatorname {id}  - g  \circ  f. And since g  \circ  f should be the projector of C onto the subspace D, \operatorname {id}  - g  \circ  f should be the projector onto E. We are thus led to proving p = d  \circ  h + h  \circ  d is indeed a projector.
\begin {aligned}       p_k  \circ  p_k &= (d_{k+1}  \circ  h_k + h_{k-1}  \circ  d_k)  \circ  (d_{k+1}  \circ  h_k + h_{k-1}  \circ  d_k)  \\        &= d_{k+1}  \circ   \overbrace {h_k  \circ  d_{k+1}  \circ  h_k}^{h_k} + d_{k+1}  \circ   \overbrace {h_k  \circ  h_{k-1}}^{0}  \circ  d_k  \\        & \qquad  + h_{k-1}  \circ   \underbrace {d_k  \circ  d_{k+1}}_{0}  \circ  h_k +  \underbrace {h_{k-1}  \circ  d_k  \circ  h_{k-1}}_{h_{k-1}}  \circ  d_k  \\        &= d_{k+1}  \circ  h_k + h_{k-1}  \circ  d_k = p_k.      \end {aligned}
Therefore we conclude that p_k splits C_k  \cong  D_k  \oplus  E_k. More over, p  \circ  d = d  \circ  h  \circ  d = d  \circ  p, meaning p is a chain map, and therefore the splitting is compatible with the boundary operator. Since h  \circ  p = p  \circ  h = h  \circ  d  \circ  h = h, the homotopy is also compatible with the splitting, so we can restrict it onto E_k to get a homotopy from \operatorname {id} _E to 0.

